00:04:53.957 --> 00:04:54.830
It's right in that.

00:04:54.830 --> 00:04:56.870
So the third function of money--

00:04:56.870 --> 00:05:01.520
store value, medium of
exchange, a unit of account.

00:05:01.520 --> 00:05:03.710
So stable pricing
is about making sure

00:05:03.710 --> 00:05:07.880
that unit of accounting,
that unit of pricing,

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:08.990
has some stability.

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:16.930
So price stability is
really about money.

00:05:16.930 --> 00:05:20.810
And it also promotes an economy.

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:24.390
They sit at the center of the
money system, central banks.

00:05:24.390 --> 00:05:27.080
At first a check on
the king to make sure

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:28.790
that the king didn't
overspend when

00:05:28.790 --> 00:05:31.745
he was at war with another
king in another country.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:38.900
That's where it all
started, but they sit right

00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:40.760
at the center of money.

00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:42.980
So the four things
we talked about,

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:50.510
they managed the nation's
Fiat money in every country--

00:05:50.510 --> 00:05:53.540
the supply, the price,
the payment systems.

00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:58.000
Payment systems are how
we move money around.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.933
So if you really want
to just boil it down,

00:06:00.933 --> 00:06:02.100
you can take a whole course.

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:03.505
There's wonderful
professors here

00:06:03.505 --> 00:06:04.630
that teach central banking.

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:09.750
But I'd say manage the
nation's Fiat money.

00:06:09.750 --> 00:06:12.540
Oversee the banking system,
because the banking system

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:17.370
is a way to basically move
money around the system

00:06:17.370 --> 00:06:19.290
and provides credit--

00:06:19.290 --> 00:06:22.200
Tom, what does a bank do
when it provides credit?

00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:26.892
Just use the word "money"
somewhere in your definition.

00:06:26.892 --> 00:06:29.607
STUDENT: It expands
the quantity of money.

00:06:29.607 --> 00:06:31.440
GARY GENSLER: Expands
the quantity of money.

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:34.472
And how does it do that?

00:06:34.472 --> 00:06:35.430
STUDENT: Lending money.

00:06:35.430 --> 00:06:37.260
GARY GENSLER: Lending money.

00:06:37.260 --> 00:06:41.430
So banks stand in between
investors or savers.

00:06:41.430 --> 00:06:43.530
We can call them depositors.

00:06:43.530 --> 00:06:46.050
So on the one hand, you have
depositors or investors.

00:06:46.050 --> 00:06:48.300
On the other hand,
you have borrowers.

00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:50.590
And banks are just
in the middle.

00:06:50.590 --> 00:06:53.640
And that's why it's called
financial intermediation--

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:56.863
intermediates, they're
just in the middle.

00:06:56.863 --> 00:06:58.530
It's more than just
being in the middle.

00:06:58.530 --> 00:07:01.260
I mean, it's a big role, but--

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:05.790
So the banks in the middle
are all about money.

00:07:05.790 --> 00:07:08.690
And so central banks
want to get involved

00:07:08.690 --> 00:07:11.660
to manage those institutions.

00:07:11.660 --> 00:07:17.610
Initially, commercial banks
came before central banks.

00:07:17.610 --> 00:07:19.770
Commercial banks
were around, and they

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:28.130
kept failing, even in a time
of the small Italian states.

00:07:28.130 --> 00:07:31.760
They would fail, and there
were some family usually,

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:34.370
or central authority
that helped out.

00:07:34.370 --> 00:07:36.740
And ultimately, the
central banks seem to--

00:07:36.740 --> 00:07:39.140
today, it seems like the
central banks came first.

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:41.450
But the commercial
banks kind of came first

00:07:41.450 --> 00:07:45.700
and then there was a central
way to protect the system.

00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:50.410
Central banks are bankers
to their own governments.

00:07:50.410 --> 00:07:54.340
Paul Tucker, who now teaches
over at the Harvard Kennedy

00:07:54.340 --> 00:07:56.720
School, but Paul Tucker
just came out with a book--

00:07:56.720 --> 00:07:59.140
he was the deputy governor
of the Bank of England--

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:03.250
about the unelected power.

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:05.200
Central banks are
unelected usually.

00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:08.420
They're don't stand
before the voters,

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:12.910
but they have a tremendous
amount of authority.

00:08:12.910 --> 00:08:16.480
So the four types of
buckets of things they do.

