00:25:35.918 --> 00:25:36.810
That is correct.

00:25:36.810 --> 00:25:39.060
They said, we can't
use this authority.

00:25:39.060 --> 00:25:44.060
And then we all know
in the history books

00:25:44.060 --> 00:25:47.910
it's written how that fateful
week in September of 2008,

00:25:47.910 --> 00:25:49.940
then everything falls bust.

00:25:49.940 --> 00:25:54.840
Because there was uncertainty
in the marketplace.

00:25:54.840 --> 00:25:56.480
And so what they
did next, Kelly--

00:25:56.480 --> 00:25:58.827
so they were using
traditional authorities.

00:25:58.827 --> 00:26:00.410
And what they did
next is they started

00:26:00.410 --> 00:26:03.397
to test the limits of
their legal authority,

00:26:03.397 --> 00:26:05.480
along with the Treasury
Department and the Federal

00:26:05.480 --> 00:26:08.210
Deposit Insurance
Corporation, and they put

00:26:08.210 --> 00:26:10.400
a series of other things in.

00:26:10.400 --> 00:26:14.030
And under an old authority of
the Federal Deposit Insurance

00:26:14.030 --> 00:26:16.280
Corporation, they
actually guaranteed

00:26:16.280 --> 00:26:22.610
all debts of the banking system
in the US for a period of time.

00:26:22.610 --> 00:26:24.410
Under other authorities,
they figured out

00:26:24.410 --> 00:26:29.300
how to put a guarantee
on money market funds.

00:26:29.300 --> 00:26:32.450
It was about $2 trillion
in money market funds.

00:26:32.450 --> 00:26:36.110
All of these almost
extra legal authorities.

00:26:36.110 --> 00:26:41.180
I mean, they were not written
right into congressional law,

00:26:41.180 --> 00:26:43.070
but they pushed the
outer boundaries.

00:26:43.070 --> 00:26:45.680
And we knew when
Larry Lessig was here

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:48.170
he said that every contract
has some ambiguity.

00:26:48.170 --> 00:26:50.450
Every law has some ambiguity.

00:26:50.450 --> 00:26:52.760
And the best lawyers at the
Federal Reserve, the best

00:26:52.760 --> 00:26:55.430
lawyers at the US Department
of Treasury and elsewhere

00:26:55.430 --> 00:26:58.020
were thinking, where
is the ambiguity?

00:26:58.020 --> 00:27:04.520
And can we use that uncertainty
in the law to save the system?

00:27:04.520 --> 00:27:06.080
And then they went to Congress.

00:27:06.080 --> 00:27:08.750
They went to Congress and
asked for $700 billion.

00:27:08.750 --> 00:27:13.830
When Hank Paulson Treasury
Secretary went to Congress,

00:27:13.830 --> 00:27:15.390
they sent a four
page, but it might

00:27:15.390 --> 00:27:19.320
have been three page legislative
request for $700 billion.

00:27:19.320 --> 00:27:24.970
I remember I first read
that three or four page

00:27:24.970 --> 00:27:29.650
request, because then a senator
from New York, Hillary Clinton,

00:27:29.650 --> 00:27:31.450
asked me, this thing's come up.

00:27:31.450 --> 00:27:33.760
Will you read it and
give me your advice?

00:27:33.760 --> 00:27:35.830
It didn't take me long
to read three pages.

00:27:35.830 --> 00:27:38.260
It was an outright
request for $700 billion.

00:27:38.260 --> 00:27:40.480
It finally did pass.

00:27:40.480 --> 00:27:43.120
It first failed in the
House of Representatives.

00:27:43.120 --> 00:27:48.730
It became, I think, a couple
hundred page document.

00:27:48.730 --> 00:27:53.110
But $700 billion of US taxpayer
money went to the treasury,

00:27:53.110 --> 00:27:56.510
and the treasury then
lended out and so forth.

00:27:56.510 --> 00:27:57.690
So it was multiple things.

00:27:57.690 --> 00:27:59.260
10 years later--

00:27:59.260 --> 00:28:01.570
10 years later, a
law here, Dodd-Frank,

00:28:01.570 --> 00:28:04.720
limits some of what the
federal government can do.

00:28:04.720 --> 00:28:09.470
It tightened the ability
to be the fire department

00:28:09.470 --> 00:28:13.400
in the midst of a raging fire.

00:28:13.400 --> 00:28:16.562
And there's lively
public debate recently.

00:28:16.562 --> 00:28:18.770
Tim Geithner, who was Treasury
Secretary at the time,

00:28:18.770 --> 00:28:20.720
has come out publicly,
and Ben Bernanke,

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:23.178
I think, and they've written
an Op-Ed and some other pieces

00:28:23.178 --> 00:28:26.150
saying, it would be good to
loosen some of those Dodd-Frank

00:28:26.150 --> 00:28:27.710
restrictions.

00:28:27.710 --> 00:28:29.210
But there's others
on the other side

00:28:29.210 --> 00:28:32.720
who have said, no, we need to
keep those restrictions tight.

00:28:32.720 --> 00:28:35.900
Because if the restrictions are
loose, then we have something

00:28:35.900 --> 00:28:37.510
called moral hazard.

00:28:37.510 --> 00:28:40.590
Does anybody know what
moral hazard might be?

00:28:43.650 --> 00:28:47.800
