00:55:56.310 --> 00:55:57.977
STUDENT: What do
central banks currently

00:55:57.977 --> 00:55:59.668
use to manage whose
deposits are whose?

00:55:59.668 --> 00:56:00.710
GARY GENSLER: Whose what?

00:56:00.710 --> 00:56:03.300
STUDENT: Like if it's Morgan
Stanley's deposits or Goldman

00:56:03.300 --> 00:56:05.800
Sachs' deposits, when
they exchange deposits

00:56:05.800 --> 00:56:08.730
within the central bank, what do
they currently use to manage--

00:56:08.730 --> 00:56:12.450
GARY GENSLER: They use various
forms of traditional databases,

00:56:12.450 --> 00:56:15.240
and I'm not going to
pretend that I know exactly

00:56:15.240 --> 00:56:16.740
each of those databases.

00:56:16.740 --> 00:56:20.520
But usually, for
interbank money,

00:56:20.520 --> 00:56:23.940
as you've talked about Morgan
Stanley or Goldman Sachs,

00:56:23.940 --> 00:56:27.120
they would call it the Real
Time Gross Settlement System,

00:56:27.120 --> 00:56:29.020
RTGS system.

00:56:29.020 --> 00:56:32.670
But the actual underlying
database structure

00:56:32.670 --> 00:56:35.520
frankly probably goes
back to batch processing.

00:56:35.520 --> 00:56:37.560
Most of them are still
batch processing.

00:56:37.560 --> 00:56:41.220
In the US, I think we'll
roll out a faster payment

00:56:41.220 --> 00:56:45.530
structure in 2020.

00:56:45.530 --> 00:56:48.410
And Sriham who was
visiting with us,

00:56:48.410 --> 00:56:52.370
was on a whole big advisory
group to the Federal Reserve

00:56:52.370 --> 00:56:53.430
to do that.

00:56:53.430 --> 00:56:56.210
Does that help a little bit?

00:56:56.210 --> 00:56:59.060
But the question really is,
could blockchain technology

00:56:59.060 --> 00:57:02.180
inspire the next generation
for the mid 2020s

00:57:02.180 --> 00:57:04.010
for any of these countries?

00:57:04.010 --> 00:57:07.310
To have 24 hour,
seven days a week,

00:57:07.310 --> 00:57:10.430
but also no one
central place where

00:57:10.430 --> 00:57:13.820
the ledger is kept, with
multiple parties sharing

00:57:13.820 --> 00:57:15.480
the ledger.

00:57:15.480 --> 00:57:16.983
And as Alin said,
but wait a minute,

00:57:16.983 --> 00:57:18.400
wouldn't a central
bank still want

00:57:18.400 --> 00:57:21.440
to have authority
over the protocol?

00:57:21.440 --> 00:57:24.730
The protocol amongst
20 or 50 banks.

00:57:24.730 --> 00:57:27.970
And the answer is
probably yes, but they're

00:57:27.970 --> 00:57:30.640
trying to explore what's
the most resilient system.

00:57:33.170 --> 00:57:36.020
So central bank
digital currencies.

00:57:36.020 --> 00:57:38.720
Central banks, of course,
already issue digital reserves.

00:57:38.720 --> 00:57:40.550
So the real question is this.

00:57:40.550 --> 00:57:43.550
Should access be
given to others?

00:57:43.550 --> 00:57:47.400
Should it be expanded
to the retail public?

00:57:47.400 --> 00:57:49.882
And so these were the
ones we chatted about.

