00:59:12.620 --> 00:59:14.660
I would say that in
my conversations--

00:59:14.660 --> 00:59:16.520
and Robleh Ali has
many more of them.

00:59:16.520 --> 00:59:19.340
But my conversations
with central bankers,

00:59:19.340 --> 00:59:22.970
it's a mixture of the first
one-- the one Alin did say.

00:59:22.970 --> 00:59:26.660
And then, basically
the third one.

00:59:26.660 --> 00:59:28.340
Credit allocation.

00:59:28.340 --> 00:59:32.360
That they feel like if we insert
the central bank more directly

00:59:32.360 --> 00:59:36.250
into taking retail
deposits, are we

00:59:36.250 --> 00:59:38.270
going to be inserting
the central bank more

00:59:38.270 --> 00:59:40.820
into credit allocation?

00:59:40.820 --> 00:59:45.580
Or in essence, if we shrink
the need for commercial banks,

00:59:45.580 --> 00:59:48.650
are we somehow shrinking
the credit allocation

00:59:48.650 --> 00:59:50.890
in the economy?

00:59:50.890 --> 00:59:53.340
So in normal times,
they worry, in essence,

00:59:53.340 --> 00:59:56.580
about credit and the
extension of credit.

00:59:56.580 --> 00:59:59.340
And in crisis, they
worry about being--

00:59:59.340 --> 01:00:03.310
that it would
destabilize the system.

01:00:03.310 --> 01:00:07.000
That's been my experience
talking just in these eight

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:09.530
months to central bankers.

